events.name: HistoriCorps is working with the Angeles National Forest to restore Vincent’s Cabin, August 28th-September 2nd.
events.description:
Learn more and RSVP here: https://historicorps.org/vincents-cabin-ca-2022/


Located at roughly 7,000 feet of elevation on Mount Baden-Powell is the Big Horn Mine, which was named after the big horn sheep a man named Charles Tom Vincent was hunting at the time he discovered it in 1891. Vincent and a fellow prospector laid claim to the mine, and the cabin Vincent inhabited - the site of this HistoriCorps project - was his residence. The mine and cabin are located on Gabrielino-Tongva Nation land. Hype around developing the mine was significant; investors advertised their anticipated profits to be in the neighborhood of $8M (roughly $267M in today's dollars). These claims were eventually proven to be overblown, with profits only weighing at $1M ($32M today). Over time, several companies purchased and sold the mine. The latest owner purchased the Big Horn in 1981, but by 1985, the mine was determined to be unproductive. You can read a full history of the mine here.

 




 



·         Dates: August 28 - September 2

·         Location: About 90 minutes northeast of Pasadena, CA

·         Logistics: We will camp at the Jackson Flat Group Campground! Tents and truck campers can access this campsite. 

·         Scope of Work: Volunteers will work to stabilize Vincent's Cabin by installing new posts, beams, and brace as well as perform exterior maintenance and apply wood preservatives. 

·         Project Leaders: Project Supervisor: Jason Benson! Crew Leader: Amelia Best!

·         Need to Know: It's free to volunteer! We provide all meals, tools, and training; volunteers are responsible for their own transit to the site, as well as personal camping equipment, work gloves, work clothes (buying used is fine!) and sturdy boots (not sneakers/light hikers).

events.name: Join Lowelifes for trail work Labor Day Weekend
events.description:
Lowelifes has made significant progress restoring the burned and heavily-damaged Gabrilieno NRT and Kenyon Devore trails in the 2020 Bobcat Fire burn zone. On Labor Day weekend, we will continue our fire recovery efforts on the historic Silver Moccasin NRT. As you can see from the photo above, Silver Moc was also torched down to the soil, but flora is growing back, including in the trail tread.
Give us a holler if you'd like to help work on September 3 - 4! 

If you only have time to work one day, you are welcome to attend Saturday only. To entice you to stay for both days, we will offer a tasty dinner on Saturday night, including a veggie option!

Please email us to RSVP and for more information.

board@lowelifesrcc.org
